76561198060219701,Recommended,287900,33329718,Posted: 6 July,all,lostcraft,"Summary:If you prefer a forgiving, flashy kind of pinball, PFX 2 might be more to your liking, but if you (like me) like your pinball a bit more realistic and / or already know Timeshock from the 90s, don't hesitate to shell out the money and get your fix!Highly recommended!The Long One:I was very happy to see Pro Pinball return to the PC- I loved the series back in the day and Timeshock is the shiny crown jewel of the four PP tables. Hells, I still have the original CDs in a box somewhere :DIf you're more familiar with recent videogame pinball, prepare for a surprise. Timeshock is a pretty accurate simulation, with very accurate physics and a steep learning curve. This is a game where you can pull off tricks like dead stops, airballs, soft and hard nudges and a couple other trickery that work on an actual physical table. And you wil lneed a certain bit of finesse because Timeshock is not an easy table to beat. Some shots require carefull juggling of the silver ball, and the layout is complex enough to require a bit of adjustment.But there's a lot waiting for you.Like most pinball tables, the ""story"" is less than stellar. Some scientist tinkered with something really experimental and accidentally scattered the whole universe, which is BAD. So she jumped into her time-machine and got bcak into her past which is your present and now you must save the universe. For some reason, this involves a lot of pinball.The Timeshock table is a highly stylized beast of a pinball. Center stage is a glowy green crystal, surrounded by figurines representing several time zones. Timeshock mines its time-travel theme for all it's worth: The goal of the game is to collect fuel and crystals in four eras, time-warp between said eras and not only rack a lot of points, but also save the universe by reaching the wizard mode and create an anti-timeshock.The amount of modes and little surprises the game crams into one table is astonishing. There is a clear structure: Enter time zone, find fuel, power up the warp engine, lock balls into time machine, then leave the era and snatch a crystal fragment on the way... but there's so much more, from unique missions to ramp frenzies and the elusive midnight mode. Even after months wort of playing time (pre-Steam) I am sure I haven't seen everything Timeshock has in store.The ""Ultra"" already signifies that this is not the original, which IS a bit dated. Ultra Timeshock looks much better than the pre-rendered table of old, with crisp dynamic lighting, beautiful reflextions and colourful flashy lights. It stays true to its roots though: This is not an over-the-top ""videogame"", it's a honest-to-god simulation. The table is presented without scrolling, there are no animated characters suddenly assaulting your balls, and the stylized look creates a somewhat sparse background for the silver ball. This may make you frown, but the stellar soundtrack and the hilariously hammy voice-acting will turn that frown upside down.A fun little extra is the ""glassless"" mode: At any time you can remove the table glass and move the balls around with your mouse, and this is actually a valid way to get to know the table and figure out how to beat missions. It's a gimmick but it does have its use.All in all, Timeshock is a table for pinball enthusiasts longing for a hard, honest simulation. It takes time to rack up decent scores, and mastering the whole table may well take a few weeks, but it's great glorious fun."
